<tree expanded="true" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Person"><frontmatter> <anchor>27108</anchor> <addr>masanoriogino</addr>  <route>masanoriogino.xml</route>   <title>Masanori Ogino</title> <meta name="external">https://trail.brackets-salad.com/index.xml</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Feature"><frontmatter> <anchor>27110</anchor> <addr>jms-0072</addr>  <route>jms-0072.xml</route> <date>August 14, 2023</date>  <title>Rudimentary support for XML attributes</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>When <link href="jms-005P.xml" type="local" title="Forester">forester</link> encounters an undefined function, it automatically passes through to the XML output. For instance, if the function <code>\myfun</code> is not defined, then the <link href="jms-005P.xml" type="local" title="Forester">forester</link> code <code>\myfun{hello}</code> will render to the XML code <code>&lt;myfun&gt;hello&lt;/myfun&gt;</code>. <strong>The <link href="jms-006Z.xml" type="local" title="Forester 2.3">forester 2.3</link> extends this fall-through behavior to support XML attributes.</strong></p><p>In particular, if you write <code>\myfun{key1}{value1}{key2}{value2}{hello}</code>, <link href="jms-005P.xml" type="local" title="Forester">forester</link> will render the following XML code:</p><pre>&lt;myfun key1=&quot;value1&quot; key2=&quot;value2&quot;&gt;
  hello
&lt;/myfun&gt;
</pre><p>Thanks to <link href="masanoriogino.xml" type="local" title="Masanori Ogino">Masanori Ogino</link> for suggesting this feature, and welcome to the <link href="https://lists.sr.ht/~jonsterling/forester-discuss" type="external"><link href="jms-005P.xml" type="local" title="Forester">forester</link> community</link>!.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>